Query Performance Prediction in Web Search 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:Current prediction techniques, which are generally designed for content based queries and are typically evaluated on relatively homogenous test collections of small sizes, face serious challenges in web search environments where collections are significantly more heterogeneous and different types of retrieval tasks exist .
1-2:In this paper, we present three techniques to address these challenges .
1-3:We focus on performance prediction for two types of queries in web search environments: content based and Named Page finding .
1-4:Our evaluation is mainly performed on the GOV2 collection .
1-5:In addition to evaluating our models for the two types of queries separately, we consider a more challenging and realistic situation that the two types of queries are mixed together without prior information on query types .
1-6:To assist prediction under the mixed query situation, a novel query classifier is adopted .
1-7:Results show that our prediction of web query performance is substantially more accurate than the current stateof the art prediction techniques .
1-8:Consequently, our paper provides a practical approach to performance prediction in realworld web settings .
1-9:H.3.3 [Information Storage and Retrieval]: Information Search .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Query performance prediction has many applications in a variety of information retrieval areas such as improving retrieval consistency, query refinement, and distributed IR .
2-2:The importance of this problem has been recognized by IR researchers and a number of new methods have been proposed for prediction recently [1, 2, 17] .
2-3:Most work on prediction has focused on the traditional ad hoc retrieval task where query performance is measured according to topical relevance .
2-4:These prediction models are evaluated on TREC document collections which typically consist of no more than one million relatively homogenous newswire articles .
2-5:With the popularity and influence of the Web, prediction techniques that will work well for web style queries are highly preferable .
2-6:However, web search environments pose significant challenges to current prediction models that are mainly designed for traditional TREC settings .
2-7:Here we outline some of these challenges .
2-8:First, web collections, which are much larger than conventional TREC collections, include a variety of documents that are different in many aspects such as quality and style .
2-9:Current prediction techniques can be vulnerable to these characteristics of web collections .
2-10:For example, the reported prediction accuracy of the ranking robustness technique and the clarity technique on the GOV2 collection (a large web collection) is significantly worse compared to the other TREC collections [1] .
2-11:Similar prediction accuracy on the GOV2 collection using another technique is reported in [2], confirming the difficult of predicting query performance on a large web collection .
2-12:Furthermore, web search goes beyond the scope of the ad hoc retrieval task based on topical relevance .
2-13:For example, the Named Page finding task, which is a navigational task, is also popular in web retrieval .
2-14:Query performance prediction for the NP task is still necessary since NP retrieval performance is far from perfect .
2-15:In fact, according to the report on the NP task of the 2005 Terabyte Track [3], about 40% of the test queries perform poorly (no correct answer in the first 10 search results) even in the best run from the top group .
2-16:To our knowledge, little research has explicitly addressed the problem of NP query performance prediction .
2-17:Current prediction models devised for content based queries will be less effective for NP queries considering the fundamental differences between the two .
2-18:Third, in real world web search environments, user queries are usually a mixture of different types and prior knowledge about the type of each query is generally unavailable .
2-19:The mixed query situation raises new problems for query performance prediction .
2-20:For instance, we may need to incorporate a query classifier into prediction models .
2-21:Despite these problems, the ability to handle this situation is a crucial step towards turning query performance prediction from an interesting research topic into a practical tool for web retrieval .
2-22:In this paper, we present three techniques to address the above challenges that current prediction models face in Web search environments .
2-23:Our work focuses on query performance prediction for the content based (ad hoc) retrieval task and the name page finding task in the context of web retrieval .
2-24:Our first technique, called weighted information gain (WIG), makes use of both single term and term proximity features to estimate the quality of top retrieved documents for prediction .
2-25:We find that WIG offers consistent prediction accuracy across various test collections and query types .
2-26:Moreover, we demonstrate that good prediction accuracy can be achieved for the mixed query situation by using WIG with the help of a query type classifier .
2-27:Query feedback and first rank change, which are our second and third prediction techniques, perform well for content based queries and NP queries respectively .
2-28:Our main contributions include: (1) considerably improved prediction accuracy for web content based queries over several state of the art techniques .
2-29:(2) new techniques for successfully predicting NP query performance .
2-30:(3) a practical and fully automatic solution to predicting mixed query performance .
2-31:In addition, one minor contribution is that we find that the robustness score [1], which was originally proposed for performance prediction, is helpful for query classification. .
3 RELATED WORK :
3-1:As we mentioned in the introduction, a number of prediction techniques have been proposed recently that focus on contentbased queries in the topical relevance (ad hoc) task .
3-2:We know of no published work that addresses other types of queries such as NP queries, let alone a mixture of query types .
3-3:Next we review some representative models .
3-4:The major difficulty of performance prediction comes from the fact that many factors have an impact on retrieval performance .
3-5:Each factor affects performance to a different degree and the overall effect is hard to predict accurately .
3-6:Therefore, it is not surprising to notice that simple features, such as the frequency of query terms in the collection [4] and the average IDF of query terms [5], do not predict well .
3-7:In fact, most of the successful techniques are based on measuring some characteristics of the retrieved document set to estimate topic difficulty .
3-8:For example, the clarity score [6] measures the coherence of a list of documents by the KL divergence between the query model and the collection model .
3-9:The robustness score [1] quantifies another property of a ranked list: the robustness of the ranking in the presence of uncertainty .
3-10:Carmel et al .
3-11:[2] found that the distance measured by the Jensen Shannon divergence between the retrieved document set and the collection is significantly correlated to average precision .
3-12:Vinay et al.[7] proposed four measures to capture the geometry of the top retrieved documents for prediction .
3-13:The most effective measure is the sensitivity to document perturbation, an idea somewhat similar to the robustness score .
3-14:Unfortunately, their way of measuring the sensitivity does not perform equally well for short queries and prediction accuracy drops considerably when a state of the art retrieval technique (like Okapi or a language modeling approach) is adopted for retrieval instead of the tf idf weighting used in their paper [16] .
3-15:The difficulties of applying these models in web search environments have already been mentioned .
3-16:In this paper, we mainly adopt the clarity score and the robustness score as our baselines .
3-17:We experimentally show that the baselines, even after being carefully tuned, are inadequate for the web environment .
3-18:One of our prediction models, WIG, is related to the Markov random field model for information retrieval [8] .
3-19:The MRF model directly models term dependence and is found be to highly effective across a variety of test collections (particularly web collections) and retrieval tasks .
3-20:This model is used to estimate the joint probability distribution over documents and queries, an important part of WIG .
3-21:The superiority of WIG over other prediction techniques based on unigram features, which will be demonstrated later in our paper, coincides with that of MRF for retrieval .
3-22:In other word, it is interesting to note that term dependence, when being modeled appropriately, can be helpful for both improving and predicting retrieval performance. .
4 PREDICTION MODELS :
4-1:3.1 Weighted Information Gain This section introduces a weighted information gain approach that incorporates both single term and proximity features for predicting performance for both content based and Named Page finding queries .
4-2:Given a set of queries Q={Qs} (s=1,2,..N) which includes all possible user queries and a set of documents D={Dt} (t=1,2…M), we assume that each query document pair (Qs,Dt) is manually judged and will be put in a relevance list if Qs is found to be relevant to Dt .
4-3:The joint probability P(Qs,Dt) over queries Q and documents D denotes the probability that pair (Qs,Dt) will be in the relevance list .
4-4:Such assumptions are similar to those used in [8] .
