4-37:8 differs in two aspects: (1) how to estimate P(ξ|Dt) and P(ξ|C), and (2) how to choose K .
4-38:For content based queries, P(ξ|C) is estimated by the relative frequency of feature ξ in collection C as a whole .
4-39:The estimation of P(ξ|Dt) is the same as in [8] .
4-40:Namely, we estimate P(ξ|Dt) by the relative frequency of feature ξ in Dt linearly smoothed with collection frequency P(ξ|C) .
4-41:K in Eq.8 is treated as a free parameter .
4-42:Note that K is the only free parameter in the computation of WIG for content based queries because all parameters involved in P(ξ|Dt) are assumed to be fixed by taking the suggested values in [8] .
4-43:Regarding NP queries, we make use of document structure to estimate P(ξ|Dt) and P(ξ|C) by the so called mixture of language models proposed in [10] and incorporated into the MRF model for Named Page finding retrieval in [9] .
4-44:The basic idea is that a document (collection) is divided into several fields such as the title field, the main body field and the heading field .
4-45:P(ξ|Dt) and P(ξ|C) are estimated by a linear combination of the language models from each field .
4-46:Due to space constraints, we refer the reader to [9] for details .
4-47:We adopt the exact same set of parameters as used in [9] for estimation .
4-48:With regard to K in Eq.8, we set K to 1 because the Named Page finding task heavily focuses on the first ranked document .
4-49:Consequently, there are no free parameters in the computation of WIG for NP queries .
4-50:3.2 Query Feedback In this section, we introduce another technique called query feedback for prediction .
4-51:Suppose that a user issues query Q to a retrieval system and a ranked list L of documents is returned .
4-52:We view the retrieval system as a noisy channel .
4-53:Specifically, we assume that the output of the channel is L and the input is Q .
4-54:After going through the channel, Q becomes corrupted and is transformed to ranked list L .
4-55:By thinking about the retrieval process this way, the problem of predicting retrieval effectiveness turns to the task of evaluating the quality of the channel .
4-56:In other words, prediction becomes finding a way to measure the degree of corruption that arises when Q is transformed to L .
4-57:As directly computing the degree of the corruption is difficult, we tackle this problem by approximation .
4-58:Our main idea is that we measure to what extent information on Q can be recovered from L on the assumption that only L is observed .
4-59:Specifically, we design a decoder that can accurately translate L back into new query Q" and the similarity S between the original query Q and the new query Q" is adopted as a performance predictor .
4-60:This is a sketch of how the QF technique predicts query performance .
4-61:Before filling in more details, we briefly discuss why this method would work .
4-62:There is a relation between the similarity S defined above and retrieval performance .
4-63:On the one hand, if the retrieval has strayed from the original sense of the query Q, the new query Q" extracted from ranked list L in response to Q would be very different from the original query Q .
4-64:On the other hand, a query distilled from a ranked list containing many relevant documents is likely to be similar to the original query .
4-65:Further examples in support of the relation will be provided later .
4-66:Next we detail how to build the decoder and how to measure the similarity S .
4-67:In essence, the goal of the decoder is to compress ranked list L into a few informative terms that should represent the content of the top ranked documents in L .
4-68:Our approach to this goal is to represent ranked list L by a language model (distribution over terms) .
4-69:Then terms are ranked by their contribution to the language model"s KL (Kullback Leibler) divergence from the background collection model .
4-70:Top ranked terms will be chosen to form the new query Q" .
4-71:This approach is similar to that used in Section 4.1 of [11] .
4-72:Specifically, we take three steps to compress ranked list L into query Q" without referring to the original query .
