5 EVALUATION :
5-1:We now present the results of predicting query performance by our models .
5-2:Three state of the art techniques are adopted as our baselines .
5-3:We evaluate our techniques across a variety of Web retrieval settings .
5-4:As mentioned before, we consider two types of queries, that is, content based queries and Named Page(NP) finding queries .
5-5:First, suppose that the query types are known .
5-6:We investigate the correlation between the predicted retrieval performance and the actual performance for both types of queries separately .
5-7:Results show that our methods yield considerable improvements over the baselines .
5-8:We then consider a more challenging scenario where no prior information on query types is available .
5-9:Two sub cases are considered .
5-10:In the first one, there exists only one type of query but the actual type is unknown .
5-11:We assume a mixture of the two query types in the second case .
5-12:We demonstrate that our models achieve good accuracy under this demanding scenario, making prediction practical in a real world Web search environment .
5-13:4.1 Experimental Setup Our evaluation focuses on the GOV2 collection which contains about 25 million documents crawled from web sites in the .gov domain during 2004 [3] .
5-14:We create two kinds of data set for CB queries and NP queries respectively .
5-15:For the CB type, we use the ad hoc topics of the Terabyte Tracks of 2004, 2005 and 2006 and name them TB04 adhoc, TB05 adhoc and TB06 adhoc respectively .
5-16:In addition, we also use the ad hoc topics of the 2004 Robust Track (RT04) to test the adaptability of our techniques to a non Web environment .
5-17:For NP queries, we use the Named Page finding topics of the Terabyte Tracks of 2005 and 2006 and we name them TB05 NP and TB06 NP respectively .
5-18:All queries used in our experiments are titles of TREC topics as we center on web retrieval .
5-19:Table 3 summarizes the above data sets .
