5-36:As we described in the previous section, both WIG and QF have one free parameter to set, that is, the cutoff rank K .
5-37:We train the parameter on one dataset and test on the other .
5-38:When combining WIG and QF, a simple linear combination is used and the combination weight is learned from the training data set .
5-39:From these results, we can see that our methods are considerably more accurate compared to the baselines .
5-40:We also observe that further improvements are obtained from the combination of WIG and QF, suggesting that they measure different properties of the retrieval process that relate to performance .
5-41:We discover that our methods generalize well on TB06 adhoc while the correlation for the clarity score with retrieval performance on this data set is considerably worse .
5-42:Further investigation shows that the mean average precision of TB06 adhoc is 0.342 and is about 10% better than that of the first data set .
5-43:While the other three methods typically consider the top 100 or less documents given a ranked list, the clarity method usually needs the top 500 or more documents to adequately measure the coherence of a ranked list .
5-44:Higher mean average precision makes ranked lists retrieved by different queries more similar in terms of coherence at the level of top 500 documents .
5-45:We believe that this is the main reason for the low accuracy of the clarity score on the second data set .
5-46:Though this paper focuses on a Web search environment, it is desirable that our techniques will work consistently well in other situations .
5-47:To this end, we examine the effectiveness of our techniques on the Robust 2004 Track .
5-48:For our methods, we evenly divide all of the test queries into five groups and perform five fold cross validation .
5-49:Each time we use one group for training and the remaining four groups for testing .
5-50:We make use of all of the queries for our two baselines, that is, the clarity score and the robustness score .
5-51:The parameters for our baselines are the same as those used in [1].The results shown in Table 5 demonstrate that the prediction accuracy of our methods is on a par with that of the two strong baselines .
