5-54:Furthermore, we examine the prediction sensitivity of our methods to the cutoff rank K .
5-55:With respect to WIG, it is quite robust to K on the Terabyte Tracks (2004 2006) while it prefers a small value of K like 5 on the 2004 Robust Track .
5-56:In other words, a small value of K is a nearly optimal choice for both kinds of tracks .
5-57:Considering the fact that all other parameters involved in WIG are fixed and consequently the same for the two cases, this means WIG can achieve nearly optimal prediction accuracy in two considerably different situations with exactly the same parameter setting .
5-58:Regarding QF, it prefers a larger value of K such as 100 on the Terabyte Tracks and a smaller value of K such as 25 on the 2004 Robust Track .
5-59:4.2.2 NP Queries We adopt WIG and first rank change for predicting NPquery performance .
5-60:We also try a linear combination of the two as in the previous section .
5-61:The combination weight is obtained from the other data set .
5-62:We use the correlation with the reciprocal ranks measured by the Pearson"s correlation test to evaluate prediction quality .
5-63:The results are presented in Table 6 .
5-64:Again, our baselines are the clarity score and the robustness score .
5-65:To make a fair comparison, we tune the clarity score in different ways .
5-66:We found that using the first ranked document to build the query model yields the best prediction accuracy .
5-67:We also attempted to utilize document structure by using the mixture of language models mentioned in section 3.1 .
5-68:Little improvement was obtained .
5-69:The correlation coefficients for the clarity score reported in Table 6 are the best we have found .
5-70:As we can see, our methods considerably outperform the clarity score technique on both of the runs .
5-71:This confirms our intuition that the use of a coherence based measure like the clarity score is inappropriate for NP queries .
