5-102:4.3.2 A mixture of contented based and NP queries A mixture of the two types of queries is a more realistic situation that a Web search engine will meet .
5-103:We evaluate prediction accuracy by how accurately poorly performing queries can be identified by the prediction method assuming that actual query types are unknown (but we can predict query types) .
5-104:This is a challenging task because both the predicted and actual performance for one type of query can be incomparable to that for the other type .
5-105:Next we discuss how to implement our evaluation .
5-106:We create a query pool which consists of all of the 150 ad hoc title queries from Terabyte Track 2004 2006 and all of the 433 NP queries from Terabyte Track 2005&2006 .
5-107:We divide the queries in the pool into classes: good (better than 50% of the queries of the same type in terms of retrieval performance) and bad (otherwise) .
5-108:According to these standards, a NP query with the reciprocal rank above 0.2 or a content based query with the average precision above 0.315 will be considered as good .
5-109:Then, each time we randomly select one query Q from the pool with probability p that Q is contented based .
5-110:The remaining queries are used as training data .
5-111:We first decide the type of query Q according to a query classifier .
5-112:Namely, the query classifier tells us whether query Q is NP or content based .
5-113:Based on the predicted query type and the score computed for query Q by a prediction technique, a binary decision is made about whether query Q is good or bad by comparing to the score threshold of the predicted query type obtained from the training data .
5-114:Prediction accuracy is measured by the accuracy of the binary decision .
5-115:In our implementation, we repeatedly take a test query from the query pool and prediction accuracy is computed as the percentage of correct decisions, that is, a good(bad) query is predicted to be good (bad) .
5-116:It is obvious that random guessing will lead to 50% accuracy .
5-117:Let us take the WIG method for example to illustrate the process .
5-118:Two WIG thresholds (one for NP queries and the other for content based queries) are trained by maximizing the prediction accuracy on the training data .
5-119:When a test query is labeled as the NP type by the query type classifier, it will be predicted to be good if and only if the WIG score for this query is above the NP threshold .
5-120:Similar procedures will be taken for other prediction techniques .
5-121:Now we briefly introduce the automatic query type classifier used in this paper .
5-122:We find that the robustness score, though originally proposed for performance prediction, is a good indicator of query types .
5-123:We find that on average content based queries have a much higher robustness score than NP queries .
5-124:For example, Figure 2 shows the distributions of robustness scores for NP and content based queries .
5-125:According to this finding, the robustness score classifier will attach a NP label to the query if the robustness score for the query is below (above) a threshold trained from the training data .
